Dutch tax authorities' plan to outsource VAT systems to US firms raises data sovereignty & compliance risks. As tech leaders, we must:
1. Rigorously audit vendor GDPR compliance & data residency;
2. Evaluate local/EU-cloud alternatives;
3. Embed data governance as a core requirement from project inception. Outsourcing must not compromise citizen data security.

As tech professionals, GeoHot's piece reveals how AI disrupts traditional business models by equalizing time. Key insight: Simple APIs and a tiered supply chain (especially chip design/software) prevent monopolies, but the application layer may repeat history.

Actionable steps:
1. Adopt open model interfaces (e.g., OpenRouter) to avoid vendor lock-in;
2. Monitor open-source innovation in chips/models—they may be the next infrastructure opportunity;
3. Proactively eliminate unnecessary friction in products, treating user time as a core metric.

Apple announced expanded manufacturing in Houston: first U.S. Mac mini production, simultaneous AI server capacity growth, and a new Advanced Manufacturing Center for technical training. This reflects tech giants' strategic push for supply chain security and localized AI hardware.

Recommended actions:
1. Monitor hardware engineering and manufacturing roles in Apple's Houston supply chain;
2. Analyze AI server design implications for cloud services and edge computing;
3. Consider new requirements for product security, compliance, and performance optimization from localized manufacturing.
